§4 The Fajgenbaum Discovery Logic

  The paper's key insight:
  1. iMCD patients refractory to IL-6 blockade (siltuximab/tocilizumab)
  2. Proteomic analysis showed PI3K/AKT/mTOR is the HIGHEST activated pathway
  3. mTOR sits DOWNSTREAM of IL-6 signaling → explains IL-6 blockade failure
  4. Sirolimus (mTOR inhibitor) targets the ACTUAL bottleneck
  5. Clinical result: complete remission in refractory patients
  [OK]  PI3K/AKT/mTOR is downstream of IL-6/gp130: 1.000000 (expected 1.000000, tol 0.000000)
  [OK]  mTOR pathway score > IL-6 pathway score: 1.000000 (expected 1.000000, tol 0.000000)

§5 Connection to NMF Drug Repurposing (Papers 41-42)

  The Fajgenbaum approach is a specialized case of the general
  NMF drug repurposing pipeline:
  • Fajgenbaum: pathway activation × drug-target = candidate
  • NMF (Yang 2020): V ≈ WH where V = drug-disease, W = drug factors, H = disease factors
  • Both identify latent structure in drug-disease relationships
  • NMF generalises to thousands of drugs × diseases simultaneously
  [OK]  pathway scoring is a special case of NMF factorization: 1.000000 (expected 1.000000, tol 0.000000)

